&gt;From article &lt;3201@ruuinf.cs.ruu.nl&gt;, by henkp@ruuinf.cs.ruu.nl (Henk P. Penning):
&gt; In article &lt;20562@boulder.Colorado.EDU&gt; huntting@sel.bldrdoc.gov (Brad Huntting) writes:
&gt; 
&gt;&gt;I am trying to access tupac-amaru.informatik.rwth-aachen.de.

rwth-aachen has not jet aquired full internet connect status, you won't be able
to reach them right now from the US. If you have access to a host in europe
you can hop over the other host.

&gt;&gt;the only servers listed anywhere official are:
&gt;&gt;uunet.uu.net, adm.brl.mil, sh.cs.net, and relay.cs.net.
&gt; 
&gt;&gt;AND THEY'RE ALL BOGUS!!!
&gt; 
[blurb deleted]

No, they are not. Intentionally there are two zones for the de.
domain, one is the official internet zone, and lists all those
subdomains in de that have aquired full internet connectivity only,
and MX records for the other domains. This zone is serveres
primarily by uunet.uu.net, with the other US servers being secondary
for that zone.

The other zone, that contains all information about the ever changing
accessible netz in germany is on unido.informatik.uni-dortmund.de.
Sites using the DNS in germany usually have a forward onto
that machine to get all those domainnames correctly resolved.

The reasons for this are obviously that we still cannot enter domains
in  the official DNS zones, that are not US-internet connected.
This is leftover from the times, where the internet was primary US based,
and is now a major political question. On the other hand one is lost
without DNS, so we set up a corresponding zone at a site central
to IP networking in germany.

As you may know, international connectivit still has it's price,
so that's why there organisations without US internet connectivity.
(For one reason, the second type of organisations without US
 internet connectivity are those that cannot fullfill the requirements
 of the US administration, eg. commercial enterprises, given that
 InterEUnet is not an academical only IP internet)

Hope that helps
-- 

